<title>Notes to the story of <i>The Wind</i></title>
<summary><i>The Wind thought to be seen, in the form of a bird, by the brother–in–law of the narrator when a child. By /han≠kass’o (L VIII.-8. 6713-6724). </i>||goo-ka-!kui (Smoke&apos;s man, or Witbooi Tooren) told |han≠kass&apos;o that he had seen the Wind at the mountains at Haarfontein (or ≠ko a xa) and had thrown a stone at it, thinking it to be a bird. As a result the Wind blew hard and took up dust.</summary><comments>1) p.6712v: Smoke&apos;s man, or Witbooi Tooren (||kabbo&apos;s son and |han≠kass&apos;o&apos;s brother-in-law), 2) p.6713v: Smoke&apos;s man&apos;s master, Jacob Kotze, 3) p.6717v: <i>Africander</i> and Farland sheep, including |xam and Dutch names for them, 4) p.6719v: the &apos;Bastaard&apos;s&apos; sheep, wagons, kraal and shepherding, 5) p.6720v: at the time of this story Smoke&apos;s man was a child, 6) p.6721v: Smoke&apos;s man&apos;s masters were Bastards (&apos;Bastaards&apos;), 7) See also <i>The Wind </i>and<i> The son of the Wind</i>, 8) This story is found in Book VIII-8</comments><date>20 April 1878 (started)</date><storypages>6713-6724</storypages><category>History (personal)</category><category>Relations with others</category><author>|han≠kass'o (Klein Jantje) (VIII)</author><keyword><kw>Wind</kw><subkw>&apos;took up&apos; dust</subkw></keyword>
